{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508033"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:01:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:01:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2707"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583373"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:15:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:15:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2707"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2707"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.07,0.06,0.02,0.76]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115545"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2707"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97548"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1251"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3202"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"7162"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42548"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115545"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three hour history of right sided face and arm weakness. The patient has some trouble speaking, with the majority of the words she says not making any contextual sense and lacking meaning. Her partner provides collateral as it is very difficult to obtain a history. She has a medical history of hypertension, and hypercholesterolaemia. Her medications include atorvastatin, amlodipine and hydrochlorothiazide. She has a 40 pack-year smoking history. She is right handed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn neurological examination, there is loss of the right naso-labial fold and lip droop on grinning but it is hard to instruct her. Due to great difficulty in following instructions, power was not assessable on the upper and lower limbs. However, it is noted that there is increased tone on the right upper and lower limbs. She has reduced pain sensation on the right compared to the left side.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following blood vessels is most likely to be affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left anterior cerebral artery","Right posterior inferior cerebellar artery","Left striatocapsular artery","Right lacunar artery","Left middle cerebral artery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll of the cerebral blood vessels have classical clinical syndromes based on the cortical lobes and subcortical areas they supply. Important to note is the handedness of the patient to help determine the dominant lobe, which in right handed people is usually the left and in left handed individuals it is 50-50 each way.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main cortical signs that occur in anterior cerebral artery (ACA), middle cerebral artery (MCA), and posterior cerebral artery (PCA) strokes include weakness, sensory disturbance, visual changes, aphasia (dominant lobe), and neglect (non-dominant).\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of this patient includes right sided hemiparesis predominantly face and arm, receptive aphasia, and right hemisensory loss in the upper limb. These symptoms are predominantly within the dominant \u003Cstrong\u003EMCA territory on the left\u003C/strong\u003E. It is important to note sensory loss and weakness are not localising signs as they can be affected in several different areas. An MCA stroke is the most common area of stroke as it comes directly off the internal carotid artery and supplies a large area of brain including the lateral portion of the frontal, parietal and temporal lobes as well as deeper branches supplying the caudate, internal capsule and thalamus. Based on the branches occluded, a number of different symptoms/signs can be present. It supplies the majority of the motor and sensory cortexes (aside from the midline which on the homunculus is predominantly the lower limbs), and the receptive deficit is from Wernicke\u0027s area being affected on the medial temporal lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA stroke in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft ACA territory\u003C/strong\u003E would result in contralateral hemiparesis, with the lower limbs more greatly affected than the upper limbs, due to the arterial supply of the ACA to the homunculus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA stroke in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eright posterior inferior cerebellar artery (PICA)\u003C/strong\u003E may lead to lateral medullary syndrome, resulting in ipsilateral ataxia, ipsilateral Horner\u2019s syndrome, dysphagia, and contralateral loss of pain and temperature sensation. Additionally, it can lead to vertigo, nystagmus and nausea as a result of involvement of the vestibular system. The patient in the stem does not fit the description of a stroke in the PICA region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Estriatocapsular region \u003C/strong\u003Eis supplied by the lenticulostriate branches of the MCA, which includes the caudate nucleus, putamen, globus pallidus, anterior and posterior limbs of the internal capsule and the subinsular area. A stroke affecting this region would result in motor deficits, but may not involve language and sensory areas to the extent such as in the case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELacunar stroke\u003C/strong\u003E may result in one of many types of lacunar stroke syndromes such as pure motor stroke, pure sensory stroke, mixed sensorimotor stroke, dysarthria and ataxic hemiparesis. Lacunar stroke typically presents with a more localised deficits as a result of its small and deep infarct, and does not fit the patient in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["For patients presenting with acute onset aphasia and dense hemiparesis/sensory loss, a left MCA stroke is quite likely."],"references":["Nogles TE, Galuska MA. Middle cerebral artery stroke. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556132/.","Heiss WD. Malignant MCA infarction: pathophysiology and imaging for early diagnosis and management decisions. Cerebrovascular dis. 2016;41:1-7. Available at: https://karger.com/ced/article/41/1-2/1/77716/Malignant-MCA-Infarction-Pathophysiology-and","Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020; Chapter 17; pages 1253-1257."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97548"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2707"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97548","links":{"